Day 5 — switch + Logic Control
1. What is switch?

switch is used when you have multiple fixed choices instead of many if-else.

👉 Cleaner than if-else when checking a single variable

2. Basic Syntax

Example 1

int day = 3;

switch(day){
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;
    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid day");
}

Example 2

char grade = 'A';

switch(grade){
    case 'A':
        System.out.println("Excellent");
        break;
    case 'B':
        System.out.println("Good");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Average");
}
3. Important Concept — break

If you forget break, execution continues (called fall-through).

Example 1 (Wrong)

int n = 1;

switch(n){
    case 1:
        System.out.println("One");
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Two");
}

Output:

One
Two

Example 2 (Correct)

switch(n){
    case 1:
        System.out.println("One");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Two");
        break;
}
4. When to Use switch vs if-else

Use switch when:

Fixed values (1,2,3… or A,B,C)

Use if-else when:

Conditions (>, <, ranges)

Example Comparison

Example 1 (if-else)

if(marks >= 90){
    System.out.println("A");
}

Example 2 (switch)

int day = 2;
switch(day){
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
}
5. Input + Switch

Example 1

import java.util.Scanner;

public class Menu {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int choice = sc.nextInt();

        switch(choice){
            case 1:
                System.out.println("Tea");
                break;
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Coffee");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Invalid");
        }
    }
}

Example 2

import java.util.Scanner;

public class Calculator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int a = sc.nextInt();
        int b = sc.nextInt();
        char op = sc.next().charAt(0);

        switch(op){
            case '+':
                System.out.println(a + b);
                break;
            case '-':
                System.out.println(a - b);
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Invalid operator");
        }
    }
}
